But for today, more narrative.

00:00:38.410 --> 00:00:39.410
ANDREW GRANT: All right.

00:00:39.410 --> 00:00:41.326
We're going to talk about
writing for computer

00:00:41.326 --> 00:00:42.850
games, or games in general.

00:00:42.850 --> 00:00:45.660
I'm here with Heather
Albano and Laura

00:00:45.660 --> 00:00:48.954
Baldwin, who have very different
experiences with writing.

00:00:48.954 --> 00:00:51.120
And so I'm just going to
go ahead and dive right in,

00:00:51.120 --> 00:00:53.830
and we'll just sort of see what
happens in this conversation.

00:00:53.830 --> 00:00:55.663
And in a bit we're going
to start opening up

00:00:55.663 --> 00:00:58.510
to questions from
you folks, then

00:00:58.510 --> 00:01:01.032
we'll sort of play
it by ear, and go on.

00:01:01.032 --> 00:01:03.490
So I want to start with-- I
want you to go ahead and answer

00:01:03.490 --> 00:01:05.190
first, Heather.

00:01:05.190 --> 00:01:07.440
What was your path towards
getting into writing

00:01:07.440 --> 00:01:09.070
for computer-- for games?

00:01:09.070 --> 00:01:11.740
Not for computer, just games?

00:01:11.740 --> 00:01:15.120
HEATHER ALBANO: I usually tell
people I got into it sideways.

00:01:15.120 --> 00:01:18.800
So my freshman year in college--
my first week of my freshman

00:01:18.800 --> 00:01:21.570
year in college I looked
out the dorm window

00:01:21.570 --> 00:01:25.060
and there were people with
boffer swords out in the quad.

00:01:25.060 --> 00:01:27.740
And my new best friend
and I looked at each other

00:01:27.740 --> 00:01:30.850
and said, I'll go check it
out, if you come with me.

00:01:30.850 --> 00:01:33.430
And so I got involved
playing with a LARP,

00:01:33.430 --> 00:01:35.530
and-- Live Action
Role Playing a game.

00:01:35.530 --> 00:01:37.900
And then I got involved
writing for it.

00:01:37.900 --> 00:01:42.840
And I did that as a hobby
for a number of years,

00:01:42.840 --> 00:01:44.760
through college and
into the real world.

00:01:44.760 --> 00:01:49.434
And in 2009 I lost
my job in marketing.

00:01:49.434 --> 00:01:51.350
It was the year that
everybody lost their job.

00:01:51.350 --> 00:01:55.260
And Adam Morse, whom
I knew from the LARP,

00:01:55.260 --> 00:01:58.320
called me and said he was
founding a games company.

00:01:58.320 --> 00:02:00.869
This is Choice of Games, which
possibly you've heard of.

00:02:00.869 --> 00:02:02.910
They've been pretty well
in the four years since.

00:02:02.910 --> 00:02:04.370
At the time it was a lark.

00:02:04.370 --> 00:02:06.300
And he said, do you
want to write for us?

00:02:06.300 --> 00:02:07.740
They never turn into anything.

00:02:07.740 --> 00:02:08.669
And I said, yeah.

00:02:08.669 --> 00:02:09.270
Why not?

00:02:09.270 --> 00:02:12.775
So it started me on a
really amazing adventure

00:02:12.775 --> 00:02:15.720
of-- started writing for
them, and now I do freelance

00:02:15.720 --> 00:02:16.900
for other people as well.

00:02:16.900 --> 00:02:18.634
And here I am.

00:02:18.634 --> 00:02:19.634
ANDREW GRANT: All right.

00:02:19.634 --> 00:02:20.630
Cool.

00:02:20.630 --> 00:02:23.800
LAURA BALDWIN: Mine, actually,
is not so dissimilar.

00:02:23.800 --> 00:02:26.750
I went to college and got
involved in the MIT Assassins

00:02:26.750 --> 00:02:28.830
Guild, which hopefully
some of you have heard of,

00:02:28.830 --> 00:02:32.570
which is another LARP, and
started writing for them.

00:02:32.570 --> 00:02:35.040
I did sit-down games.

00:02:35.040 --> 00:02:38.590
Then I went to grad school,
got a degree in immunology,

00:02:38.590 --> 00:02:40.890
and decided I didn't
want to be a biologist.

00:02:40.890 --> 00:02:43.950
Which is much like
you, losing your job.

00:02:43.950 --> 00:02:45.570
HEATHER ALBANO:
Yep, [INAUDIBLE].

00:02:45.570 --> 00:02:49.259
LAURA BALDWIN: And I got a
half-time job working with MIT,

00:02:49.259 --> 00:02:51.550
because they only had half
of a head count in the thing

00:02:51.550 --> 00:02:54.680
that I was doing, and
my other half-time

00:02:54.680 --> 00:02:57.120
job was a friend of mine who
I had written some Assassin

00:02:57.120 --> 00:03:00.320
games with and had done
some sit-downing with.

00:03:00.320 --> 00:03:04.060
Had, at a point in the past,
founded a computer game

00:03:04.060 --> 00:03:07.140
company, or been part of
creating a computer game

00:03:07.140 --> 00:03:10.960
company-- Looking Glass, I
think it was Studios firsts--

00:03:10.960 --> 00:03:12.730
And said, well, I
know that you know

00:03:12.730 --> 00:03:15.900
how to write things, and
know things about games

00:03:15.900 --> 00:03:17.480
and can work with
well with others.

00:03:17.480 --> 00:03:19.200
So do you want to
come and work for us?

00:03:19.200 --> 00:03:22.730
And since I wanted to keep
my job with the health care

00:03:22.730 --> 00:03:27.160
I worked half-time for
them and half-time for MIT,

00:03:27.160 --> 00:03:30.220
and did that for
a number of years

00:03:30.220 --> 00:03:32.500
until Looking Glass
ended up going bankrupt,

00:03:32.500 --> 00:03:34.800
and now I just work for MIT.

00:03:34.800 --> 00:03:38.400
And still do
sit-downs and stuff.

00:03:38.400 --> 00:03:41.606
But yeah, it does
seem to be about-- you

00:03:41.606 --> 00:03:42.980
get into games
first and then you

00:03:42.980 --> 00:03:44.396
have connections
with other people

00:03:44.396 --> 00:03:47.085
and they get you
into game companies.

00:03:47.085 --> 00:03:48.460
HEATHER ALBANO:
Networking works,

00:03:48.460 --> 00:03:49.840
is the moral of the story.

00:03:49.840 --> 00:03:51.048
ANDREW GRANT: It really does.

00:03:51.048 --> 00:03:52.930
LAURA BALDWIN: Meet each other.

00:03:52.930 --> 00:03:55.210
ANDREW GRANT: You
never know later.

00:03:55.210 --> 00:03:57.100
Everyone you meet
today might be helpful.

00:03:57.100 --> 00:03:57.600
Yeah.

00:03:57.600 --> 00:04:01.240
So you've both done a fair
bit of writing for games.

00:04:01.240 --> 00:04:04.449
Have you been writing
outside of games at all?

00:04:04.449 --> 00:04:06.740
HEATHER ALBANO: Do you want
to take it first this time?

00:04:06.740 --> 00:04:08.781
LAURA BALDWIN: So I work
in customer support now,

00:04:08.781 --> 00:04:11.450
and that involves a lot of
writing email back to people.

00:04:11.450 --> 00:04:15.460
That has trained me to be
concise and clear and friendly

00:04:15.460 --> 00:04:15.980
in writing.

00:04:15.980 --> 00:04:19.449
It's a little bit related,
but that's about it.

00:04:19.449 --> 00:04:20.240
HEATHER ALBANO: OK.

00:04:20.240 --> 00:04:24.270
In contrast, I do a lot of
non-game fiction writing.

00:04:24.270 --> 00:04:28.690
My dream job for years was
to be able to write novels,

00:04:28.690 --> 00:04:32.500
and it's actually less
so as I've had success

00:04:32.500 --> 00:04:35.780
in writing for games, which
is fulfilling in its own way

00:04:35.780 --> 00:04:38.750
and pays a lot better.

00:04:38.750 --> 00:04:42.030
But I've sold some short fiction
and some poetry to magazines.

00:04:42.030 --> 00:04:44.450
I've self-published two novels.

00:04:44.450 --> 00:04:47.885
And that's sort of on the hobby
side of my life these days.

00:04:47.885 --> 00:04:48.760
ANDREW GRANT: Got it.

00:04:48.760 --> 00:04:51.570
We'll come back to that
in a little bit, I think.

00:04:51.570 --> 00:04:53.710
So I want to talk about
what kinds of games

00:04:53.710 --> 00:04:55.700
you've worked on, and
so what kind of writing

00:04:55.700 --> 00:04:57.574
that you've done has
appeared in those games?

00:04:57.574 --> 00:05:02.540
And feel free to name names and
whatnot of what you worked on.

00:05:02.540 --> 00:05:04.474
Why don't head, Heather?

00:05:04.474 --> 00:05:09.250
HEATHER ALBANO: So my
professional game writing

00:05:09.250 --> 00:05:11.990
divides into three
categories pretty neatly.

00:05:11.990 --> 00:05:14.040
I've done most of it
for Choice of Games,

00:05:14.040 --> 00:05:19.310
which does multiple choice
text-based games of the Choose

00:05:19.310 --> 00:05:20.540
Your Path variety.

00:05:20.540 --> 00:05:24.260
So, kind of like the old Choose
Your Own Adventure books,

00:05:24.260 --> 00:05:28.300
if you're familiar with those,
although better-written,

00:05:28.300 --> 00:05:31.510
if I say it myself.

00:05:31.510 --> 00:05:33.670
So that's all text, right?

00:05:33.670 --> 00:05:35.700
All text all the time.

00:05:35.700 --> 00:05:38.860
I was lead writer on
Codename Cygnus two years

00:05:38.860 --> 00:05:41.330
ago now, which is an
interactive radio drama, which

00:05:41.330 --> 00:05:43.950
is sort of the same idea in
that it is all word-based,

00:05:43.950 --> 00:05:46.330
but obviously the interface
is very different.

00:05:46.330 --> 00:05:54.070
And I have done some work
for paper-and-pencil RPGs.

00:05:54.070 --> 00:05:56.809
TimeWatch by Kevin Kulp
is coming out next year

00:05:56.809 --> 00:05:58.100
and I've got some work in that.

00:05:58.100 --> 00:05:59.200
ANDREW GRANT: There's
a small world again.

00:05:59.200 --> 00:05:59.250
OK.

00:05:59.250 --> 00:06:00.054
I know Kevin Kulp.

00:06:00.054 --> 00:06:01.470
HEATHER ALBANO: I
figured you did.

00:06:01.470 --> 00:06:02.344
Looking Glass, right?

00:06:02.344 --> 00:06:03.840
Wasn't he-- no?

00:06:03.840 --> 00:06:05.620
OK.

00:06:05.620 --> 00:06:07.669
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE].

00:06:07.669 --> 00:06:08.460
ANDREW GRANT: Yeah.

00:06:08.460 --> 00:06:12.440
His wife worked for Looking
Glass, and et cetera.

00:06:12.440 --> 00:06:15.180
So talk about
interactive radio show.

00:06:15.180 --> 00:06:16.760
How does that work?

00:06:16.760 --> 00:06:19.270
HEATHER ALBANO: So you
play it off your iPod,

00:06:19.270 --> 00:06:21.880
and I think now your Android.

00:06:21.880 --> 00:06:28.140
It talks to you and at the--
it narrates what's going on.

00:06:28.140 --> 00:06:31.670
You play a spy in a
James Bond kind of world.

00:06:31.670 --> 00:06:33.920
And so it tells you the
circumstance you're in

00:06:33.920 --> 00:06:37.940
and then asks you if you want
to do this or that in response,

00:06:37.940 --> 00:06:41.000
and you say the word.

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:43.670
The voice recognition
is pretty good,

00:06:43.670 --> 00:06:45.310
but it's not
super-sophisticated.

00:06:45.310 --> 00:06:46.440
It wasn't designed to be.

00:06:46.440 --> 00:06:49.600
So you don't get to talk
back to it in a natural way,

00:06:49.600 --> 00:06:52.680
you have to save the-- it's
a little bit better than,

00:06:52.680 --> 00:06:54.750
pick a or pick b, but
you have to say the words

00:06:54.750 --> 00:06:55.555
that it gives you.

00:06:55.555 --> 00:06:56.430
ANDREW GRANT: Got it.

00:06:56.430 --> 00:06:59.260
So you can say, shoot gun,
not for a villain or whatever.

00:06:59.260 --> 00:07:00.260
HEATHER ALBANO: Exactly.

00:07:00.260 --> 00:07:02.820
Not, I draw the gun and
duck behind the-- no.

00:07:02.820 --> 00:07:05.420
I shoot the gun.

00:07:05.420 --> 00:07:06.060
But yeah.

00:07:06.060 --> 00:07:08.060
So other than that, it's
mostly multiple choice.

00:07:08.060 --> 00:07:09.059
ANDREW GRANT: All right.

00:07:09.059 --> 00:07:10.530
So the behind-the-scene
mechanics

00:07:10.530 --> 00:07:14.250
are very similar to the
multiple choice text adventure,

00:07:14.250 --> 00:07:17.711
but it's text that's going
to be heard instead of read.

00:07:17.711 --> 00:07:18.710
HEATHER ALBANO: Exactly.

00:07:18.710 --> 00:07:20.520
ANDREW GRANT: Oh, all right.

00:07:20.520 --> 00:07:21.180
Neat.

00:07:21.180 --> 00:07:22.544
And you, Laura?

00:07:22.544 --> 00:07:24.460
LAURA BALDWIN: What was
the original question?

00:07:24.460 --> 00:07:28.270
ANDREW GRANT: The original
was what sorts of stuff

00:07:28.270 --> 00:07:30.700
has-- what kinds of
games have you worked on

00:07:30.700 --> 00:07:33.400
and how did your
stuff appear in there.

00:07:33.400 --> 00:07:36.880
LAURA BALDWIN: So I was kind
of a-- since I was part-time

00:07:36.880 --> 00:07:39.570
they didn't want to put me in
charge of any specific levels

00:07:39.570 --> 00:07:43.420
or anything, so I was sort
of-- I did a lot of odd jobs.

00:07:43.420 --> 00:07:48.330
I ended up writing the manual
for System Shock 2, which

00:07:48.330 --> 00:07:51.140
was really exciting because
a lot of the time you have

00:07:51.140 --> 00:07:54.700
to write the manual before the
game mechanics are sorted out.

00:07:54.700 --> 00:07:57.780
So you would say
things like, this psi

00:07:57.780 --> 00:08:00.530
power provides defense.

00:08:00.530 --> 00:08:04.300
You really have no idea, sorry.

00:08:04.300 --> 00:08:07.170
And then in Thief
and Thief II I did

00:08:07.170 --> 00:08:09.680
a lot of sort of
like random books

00:08:09.680 --> 00:08:12.910
that are scattered around,
or dialogue that characters

00:08:12.910 --> 00:08:13.910
would say to each other.

00:08:13.910 --> 00:08:16.118
There wasn't much that
characters said to each other.

00:08:16.118 --> 00:08:18.710
And then the guards and so on
you're trying to sneak around,

00:08:18.710 --> 00:08:20.790
and the guards are
basically walking

00:08:20.790 --> 00:08:23.247
around being emitters
of what they think

00:08:23.247 --> 00:08:24.830
is going on right
now which, you know,

00:08:24.830 --> 00:08:26.650
if you're really
sneaky they're like,

00:08:26.650 --> 00:08:28.410
I have no idea
anything is going on.

00:08:28.410 --> 00:08:29.090
I am bored.

00:08:29.090 --> 00:08:30.280
I see nothing.

00:08:30.280 --> 00:08:31.320
I hear nothing.

00:08:31.320 --> 00:08:34.607
But you know, if you let
them-- if they see you briefly

00:08:34.607 --> 00:08:36.190
or hear you briefly,
then they sort of

00:08:36.190 --> 00:08:37.940
have to admit their
state which is,

00:08:37.940 --> 00:08:40.012
I am mildly suspicious
because I heard something

00:08:40.012 --> 00:08:41.220
but I don't know what it was.

00:08:41.220 --> 00:08:43.330
Or, I'm really
suspicious because I just

00:08:43.330 --> 00:08:46.540
saw Thief going that way.

00:08:46.540 --> 00:08:49.030
But you know, they're
not very bright AIs,

00:08:49.030 --> 00:08:51.290
so they don't have a
lot of different states

00:08:51.290 --> 00:08:52.180
that they can say.

00:08:52.180 --> 00:08:54.300
They have a level of
suspicion and then a level

00:08:54.300 --> 00:08:56.190
of what caused the suspicion.

00:08:56.190 --> 00:08:58.990
And there's a big
matrix of that.

00:08:58.990 --> 00:09:01.680
And then you don't
want your guards

00:09:01.680 --> 00:09:03.820
to say the same thing
every single time,

00:09:03.820 --> 00:09:06.210
so you have to have, like,
20 different things for each

00:09:06.210 --> 00:09:07.550
of those categories.

00:09:07.550 --> 00:09:10.630
And it gets kind of
tedious and difficult

00:09:10.630 --> 00:09:14.560
to come up with 20
different ways to say,

00:09:14.560 --> 00:09:17.070
I am mildly suspicious
because of a noise,

00:09:17.070 --> 00:09:20.370
without sounding like you've
been coached to say that.

00:09:20.370 --> 00:09:22.860
You know, how many natural
ways can you say that?

00:09:25.760 --> 00:09:30.065
And then yeah-- I think
that's most of it.

00:09:30.065 --> 00:09:31.065
ANDREW GRANT: All right.

00:09:31.065 --> 00:09:32.520
Yeah, that's good.

00:09:32.520 --> 00:09:34.944
And so let's jump
right into a little bit

00:09:34.944 --> 00:09:37.360
here, the difference between
writing for stuff that people

00:09:37.360 --> 00:09:40.540
are going to read versus stuff
that people are going to hear.

00:09:40.540 --> 00:09:42.520
It sounds like you've
got a lot of experience

00:09:42.520 --> 00:09:46.050
with that, with
long-form read words,

00:09:46.050 --> 00:09:47.990
and you're talking
about guards that

00:09:47.990 --> 00:09:51.220
are saying things out loud,
or also written books.

00:09:51.220 --> 00:09:52.900
And those are very
different things,

00:09:52.900 --> 00:09:54.830
I assume, in terms
of how the player's

00:09:54.830 --> 00:09:56.517
going to appreciate them.

00:09:56.517 --> 00:09:57.350
LAURA BALDWIN: Yeah.

00:09:57.350 --> 00:10:00.520
So the thing that I
learned pretty quickly

00:10:00.520 --> 00:10:04.860
about stuff that is said out
loud is that the players want

00:10:04.860 --> 00:10:07.230
it to be really,
really short, which

00:10:07.230 --> 00:10:11.200
makes it in particular
extra-hard because, you know,

00:10:11.200 --> 00:10:13.770
"huh," or "what was that?"

00:10:13.770 --> 00:10:16.870
You know, they want to have
about that much of interaction

00:10:16.870 --> 00:10:18.820
with the guard that
they're hiding from,

00:10:18.820 --> 00:10:23.230
and you have to convey all this
little settings because you

00:10:23.230 --> 00:10:24.960
want to have people
know the difference

00:10:24.960 --> 00:10:27.555
between a "huh" that's like,
"hm," or a "huh" that's like,

00:10:27.555 --> 00:10:28.300
"huh!

00:10:28.300 --> 00:10:29.800
I'm going to get you."

00:10:29.800 --> 00:10:34.340
So there's also a lot of little
stage notes, you know? "Huh.

00:10:34.340 --> 00:10:35.970
Angry."

00:10:35.970 --> 00:10:42.210
But I ended up writing a lot
of little, short dialogues

00:10:42.210 --> 00:10:43.930
for guards to be
talking to each other,

00:10:43.930 --> 00:10:47.690
or other-- it was mostly
guards-- that you could

00:10:47.690 --> 00:10:49.450
sneak by and hear,
and sometimes it

00:10:49.450 --> 00:10:51.920
was to convey information
about where something was.

00:10:51.920 --> 00:10:55.610
And sadly kind of the
first thing that we got

00:10:55.610 --> 00:10:58.590
told after the playtesting was
that those are just too long.

00:10:58.590 --> 00:11:01.137
Nobody wants to sit there for
three minutes and, you know,

00:11:01.137 --> 00:11:02.970
hide in the shadows
listening to guards talk

00:11:02.970 --> 00:11:04.220
to each other about something.

00:11:04.220 --> 00:11:07.110
Especially not more than once.

00:11:07.110 --> 00:11:09.830
And so really only one
of the conversations

00:11:09.830 --> 00:11:12.400
that was more than
four lines survived

00:11:12.400 --> 00:11:15.050
into the shipping game, which
is at the very beginning

00:11:15.050 --> 00:11:16.860
of the first level.

00:11:16.860 --> 00:11:17.870
And you can skip it.

00:11:17.870 --> 00:11:20.710
It's the guards talking to
each other in the courtyard

00:11:20.710 --> 00:11:22.565
about going to bear
bits, and you can go

00:11:22.565 --> 00:11:23.690
and you can listen to them.

00:11:23.690 --> 00:11:25.830
And it tells you a little
bit about the world.

00:11:25.830 --> 00:11:27.955
Or you can just, you know,
sneak around and go back

00:11:27.955 --> 00:11:29.000
to the secret entrance.

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:31.420
And so if you're playing
the game for the second time

00:11:31.420 --> 00:11:33.882
you do not have to
listen to all of it.

00:11:33.882 --> 00:11:35.840
ANDREW GRANT: So is there
a lot of conversation

00:11:35.840 --> 00:11:38.870
left on the cutting room
floor, as it were then?

00:11:38.870 --> 00:11:39.830
LAURA BALDWIN: Yeah.

00:11:39.830 --> 00:11:40.330
Yeah.

00:11:40.330 --> 00:11:41.180
ANDREW GRANT: Because it
wasn't until playtest that you

00:11:41.180 --> 00:11:43.310
realized that it was too long.

00:11:43.310 --> 00:11:47.760
LAURA BALDWIN: I think-- I
guess it must have been recorded

00:11:47.760 --> 00:11:53.480
because most of our guards were
being voiced by programmers,

00:11:53.480 --> 00:11:54.930
at least early on.

00:11:54.930 --> 00:11:59.536
I think we definitely kept
Dan Thron as the stupid guard.

00:11:59.536 --> 00:12:02.190
He became very popular.

00:12:02.190 --> 00:12:04.780
ANDREW GRANT: He's got
a very expressive voice.

00:12:04.780 --> 00:12:06.600
So I imagine your form
of fiction, Heather,

00:12:06.600 --> 00:12:09.260
is a little bit different
because it's a longer form

00:12:09.260 --> 00:12:10.990
to begin with, so you expect
a little bit more patience

00:12:10.990 --> 00:12:11.960
on the part of your players.

00:12:11.960 --> 00:12:12.610
HEATHER ALBANO: Yep.

00:12:12.610 --> 00:12:14.320
And also all they've
got is the words.

00:12:14.320 --> 00:12:17.290
The words are-- the
dialogue in the radio drama,

00:12:17.290 --> 00:12:19.810
for instance-- the dialogue
isn't a distraction

00:12:19.810 --> 00:12:20.590
from the mechanic.

00:12:20.590 --> 00:12:22.360
The dialogue is the mechanic.

00:12:22.360 --> 00:12:23.610
It's all they got to react to.

00:12:23.610 --> 00:12:23.860
LAURA BALDWIN: Yeah.

00:12:23.860 --> 00:12:25.530
You don't want to have--
they're not going to be saying,

00:12:25.530 --> 00:12:27.430
oh, I want to fast
forward through all this,

00:12:27.430 --> 00:12:28.450
because why would
they be playing?

00:12:28.450 --> 00:12:28.780
HEATHER ALBANO: Right.

00:12:28.780 --> 00:12:29.280
Exactly.

00:12:29.280 --> 00:12:32.390
All they're doing is listening
to other voice actors,

00:12:32.390 --> 00:12:34.240
you know, putting
together a drama

00:12:34.240 --> 00:12:38.676
and then they're responding
to it, interacting with it.

00:12:38.676 --> 00:12:41.660
The difference between--
there is a difference

00:12:41.660 --> 00:12:44.050
between writing dialogue
that will be read

00:12:44.050 --> 00:12:48.320
and writing dialogue
that will be spoken.

00:12:48.320 --> 00:12:55.080
In the Choice of Games we
have a lot more freedom.

00:12:55.080 --> 00:12:57.030
We have a lot
more-- we have a lot

00:12:57.030 --> 00:12:58.540
of things that
aren't the dialogue.

00:12:58.540 --> 00:13:03.520
You can put in a tag that
says, "hey, he said angrily."

00:13:03.520 --> 00:13:05.030
Right?

00:13:05.030 --> 00:13:07.400
Or you can say that he said
it while folding his arms

00:13:07.400 --> 00:13:11.230
or whatever, that gives the
reader a clue as to what

00:13:11.230 --> 00:13:12.410
they're dealing with.

00:13:12.410 --> 00:13:16.040
When you're writing a
radio drama all you've got

00:13:16.040 --> 00:13:19.730
is the dialogue and the
stage queues for the actors.

00:13:19.730 --> 00:13:22.430
I got a lot better at
writing dialogue very,

00:13:22.430 --> 00:13:24.219
very, very fast
out of necessity,

00:13:24.219 --> 00:13:25.260
working for that project.

00:13:27.920 --> 00:13:30.400
People who write
traditional fiction

00:13:30.400 --> 00:13:34.500
will tell you that there
shouldn't be a difference.

00:13:34.500 --> 00:13:36.980
You should always be writing
dialogue that doesn't

00:13:36.980 --> 00:13:38.990
need the prose around it.

00:13:38.990 --> 00:13:45.220
You should always be able to
get the character's personality

00:13:45.220 --> 00:13:48.320
and how they're reacting
to the particular situation

00:13:48.320 --> 00:13:53.160
just from their word choice,
which is a great gold standard.

00:13:53.160 --> 00:13:56.312
There are some writers
who do that very well.

00:13:56.312 --> 00:13:58.270
Dorothy Sayers, who wrote
a series of mysteries

00:13:58.270 --> 00:14:00.852
back in the earlier
part of the century--

00:14:00.852 --> 00:14:05.280
in the early part of the 1900s--
does this very, very, very

00:14:05.280 --> 00:14:05.780
well.

00:14:05.780 --> 00:14:08.680
You can read-- she's got--
there's pages and pages where

00:14:08.680 --> 00:14:12.060
it's just open
quotes, close quotes

00:14:12.060 --> 00:14:14.439
dialogue between two
characters and you never

00:14:14.439 --> 00:14:16.980
lose track of who's saying what
because the personalities are

00:14:16.980 --> 00:14:17.744
so very different.

00:14:17.744 --> 00:14:18.910
ANDREW GRANT: So very clear.

00:14:18.910 --> 00:14:21.100
HEATHER ALBANO:
Very, very clear.

00:14:21.100 --> 00:14:23.780
Most of the rest of
us aren't that good.

00:14:23.780 --> 00:14:27.090
That's really the gold standard.

00:14:27.090 --> 00:14:30.040
But when you've only got
dialogue to work with,

00:14:30.040 --> 00:14:32.970
you have to get that good.

00:14:32.970 --> 00:14:35.210
It forces you to think
very hard about what

00:14:35.210 --> 00:14:37.629
the different
characters are like.

00:14:37.629 --> 00:14:38.670
ANDREW GRANT: Sure, sure.

00:14:38.670 --> 00:14:42.130
I imagine the stage
direction helps a little bit.

00:14:42.130 --> 00:14:43.970
So you want to get
across he said angrily,

00:14:43.970 --> 00:14:45.400
but we can tell the
actor to do that.

00:14:45.400 --> 00:14:45.873
HEATHER ALBANO: Exactly.

00:14:45.873 --> 00:14:46.820
Yeah.

00:14:46.820 --> 00:14:48.320
ANDREW GRANT: And then,
of course, you probably

00:14:48.320 --> 00:14:49.990
want to pick actors with
different sounding voices

00:14:49.990 --> 00:14:52.010
to help it along a little
bit, and that sort of thing.

00:14:52.010 --> 00:14:52.370
HEATHER ALBANO: Yep.

00:14:52.370 --> 00:14:53.110
ANDREW GRANT: OK.

00:14:53.110 --> 00:14:54.760
HEATHER ALBANO: That's more on
the production end, but yeah.

00:14:54.760 --> 00:14:55.500
ANDREW GRANT: Sure.

00:14:55.500 --> 00:14:55.999
Sure.

00:15:00.670 --> 00:15:03.820
So one of things that a friend
of mine was talking about

00:15:03.820 --> 00:15:05.860
was, he was adapting
a Shakespearean play

00:15:05.860 --> 00:15:08.002
for a comic book form,
which is very cool.

00:15:08.002 --> 00:15:09.960
But when he did that he
said he had to take out

00:15:09.960 --> 00:15:12.860
about half the text of the
play because in the play

00:15:12.860 --> 00:15:15.840
most of the information appeared
twice, because the listener was

00:15:15.840 --> 00:15:19.470
hearing the play and you don't,
in real time, understand it.

00:15:19.470 --> 00:15:22.870
For a radio play do you give
people redundant information

00:15:22.870 --> 00:15:25.600
or do you just rely on them
paying really intense attention

00:15:25.600 --> 00:15:27.892
to it?

00:15:27.892 --> 00:15:31.460
HEATHER ALBANO: That's
an interesting question.

00:15:31.460 --> 00:15:34.390
I think I would probably have
to go back over the script

00:15:34.390 --> 00:15:35.625
to answer that for real.

00:15:38.520 --> 00:15:42.380
My recollection is that we
did a little bit of repetition

00:15:42.380 --> 00:15:44.330
to make sure that
any time the player

00:15:44.330 --> 00:15:47.670
was making a choice they
knew the context they

00:15:47.670 --> 00:15:49.360
were making the choice in.

00:15:49.360 --> 00:15:51.990
So if there had been some
dialogue they couldn't respond

00:15:51.990 --> 00:15:58.930
to they might get like a summary
from character number three.

00:15:58.930 --> 00:16:00.820
"It looks like John
wants to do this,

00:16:00.820 --> 00:16:02.350
but Mary wants to do this.

00:16:02.350 --> 00:16:03.610
What do you think, agent?

00:16:03.610 --> 00:16:04.977
What should we do?"

00:16:04.977 --> 00:16:06.768
LAURA BALDWIN: Do you
have a Go Back button

00:16:06.768 --> 00:16:08.460
so you can hear stuff again?

00:16:08.460 --> 00:16:10.543
HEATHER ALBANO: Not in the
current implementation,

00:16:10.543 --> 00:16:12.579
as far as I know.

00:16:12.579 --> 00:16:14.620
ANDREW GRANT: But it sounds
like you could almost

00:16:14.620 --> 00:16:17.057
play this game without
touching anything, is the idea.

00:16:17.057 --> 00:16:18.640
HEATHER ALBANO:
That's the idea, yeah.

00:16:18.640 --> 00:16:21.700
You can-- it does
come with a button

00:16:21.700 --> 00:16:23.940
that you can choose
visually if you like,

00:16:23.940 --> 00:16:26.690
but the idea was that you should
be able to play it in your car.

00:16:26.690 --> 00:16:27.950
ANDREW GRANT: Got it.

00:16:27.950 --> 00:16:28.370
HEATHER ALBANO: So yeah.

00:16:28.370 --> 00:16:30.270
But of course we weren't dealing
with Shakespeare, either.

00:16:30.270 --> 00:16:32.115
So it wasn't that
level of complexity.

00:16:32.115 --> 00:16:34.410
ANDREW GRANT: Well, and the
poetry must complement it.

00:16:34.410 --> 00:16:36.160
LAURA BALDWIN: Like,
in role playing games

00:16:36.160 --> 00:16:38.260
where they have a
lot of voice-overs

00:16:38.260 --> 00:16:41.032
and they have subtitles, I
usually turn the subtitles

00:16:41.032 --> 00:16:41.740
on, just in case.

00:16:41.740 --> 00:16:43.860
Like, sometimes I
miss a word or two

00:16:43.860 --> 00:16:45.680
and I'm like, I can't go back.

00:16:45.680 --> 00:16:48.007
It's a conversation
tree, you know?

00:16:48.007 --> 00:16:48.840
ANDREW GRANT: Right.

00:16:48.840 --> 00:16:49.756
HEATHER ALBANO: Right.

00:16:49.756 --> 00:16:50.940
Yes.

00:16:50.940 --> 00:16:51.900
ANDREW GRANT: That's
kind of interesting too,

00:16:51.900 --> 00:16:54.040
because a lot of the
sit-down role playing games

00:16:54.040 --> 00:16:56.690
that I've been in, a lot of
times the gamemaster's very

00:16:56.690 --> 00:16:59.290
patient with saying, wait,
what did that person say?

00:16:59.290 --> 00:17:01.620
And if you missed it, will
help you figure it out.

00:17:01.620 --> 00:17:03.971
But in this meeting you're
talking about, no, there's

00:17:03.971 --> 00:17:04.720
not a lot of help.

00:17:04.720 --> 00:17:06.369
If you missed it, you missed it.

00:17:06.369 --> 00:17:08.068
And part of the
game is, in fact,

00:17:08.068 --> 00:17:09.609
comprehension the
first time through.

00:17:09.609 --> 00:17:12.736
That's kind of neat.

00:17:12.736 --> 00:17:13.319
So, all right.

00:17:13.319 --> 00:17:17.130
So you've talked a little
bit about this already,

00:17:17.130 --> 00:17:18.937
but all these
things are placing,

00:17:18.937 --> 00:17:21.020
pretty much, a lot of
constraints on your writing.

00:17:21.020 --> 00:17:22.520
You know, you're
talking about-- you

00:17:22.520 --> 00:17:25.569
have to get across ideas
for dialogue alone.

00:17:25.569 --> 00:17:28.259
And I think it's
kind of-- there's

00:17:28.259 --> 00:17:30.675
a difference between-- there's
conversation that gives you

00:17:30.675 --> 00:17:31.740
an idea of who the
characters are,

00:17:31.740 --> 00:17:33.406
or just sort of some
filler, and there's

00:17:33.406 --> 00:17:35.990
conversation which has got
vital information in it.

00:17:35.990 --> 00:17:38.240
You might know before you
write that conversation what

00:17:38.240 --> 00:17:39.680
that information is.

00:17:39.680 --> 00:17:42.560
Does that change
how you approach

00:17:42.560 --> 00:17:44.215
that writing,
knowing that you have

00:17:44.215 --> 00:17:46.090
to stick some important
information in there?

00:17:48.965 --> 00:17:50.840
Or do you now think
about it that way at all,

00:17:50.840 --> 00:17:51.920
and I'm just off in the field?

00:17:51.920 --> 00:17:53.961
HEATHER ALBANO: No, I've
got to think about that.

00:17:53.961 --> 00:18:03.240
So I think every scene
has a particular point

00:18:03.240 --> 00:18:05.200
you're driving towards.

00:18:05.200 --> 00:18:07.080
If there are multiple
choices in a scene--

00:18:07.080 --> 00:18:09.010
I'm thinking now
Choice Of as well as

00:18:09.010 --> 00:18:15.026
Cygnus-- then every choice has a
particular piece of information

00:18:15.026 --> 00:18:17.150
that you're needing to get
across so the player can

00:18:17.150 --> 00:18:18.910
make the choice.

00:18:18.910 --> 00:18:21.160
It's not quite a constraint
in bad way, though.

00:18:21.160 --> 00:18:22.950
It's more of-- I don't know.

00:18:22.950 --> 00:18:25.360
It's a more positive
word than that.

00:18:25.360 --> 00:18:27.860
I feel like I've actually
had the good fortune

00:18:27.860 --> 00:18:31.666
to be remarkably unconstrained
in the writing I've

00:18:31.666 --> 00:18:33.520
done for games,
because so much of it

00:18:33.520 --> 00:18:35.380
has been text-based
and dialogue-driven.

00:18:35.380 --> 00:18:37.630
I think if you want to talk
about constraints, writing

00:18:37.630 --> 00:18:41.557
for actual video games is the--

00:18:41.557 --> 00:18:42.890
LAURA BALDWIN: So, I mean, Yeah.

00:18:42.890 --> 00:18:45.930
The little grid of
"I'm suspicious"

00:18:45.930 --> 00:18:47.120
is very constraining.

00:18:47.120 --> 00:18:50.070
But I mean, to some
extent the constraints are

00:18:50.070 --> 00:18:52.750
what tell you what you
have to write about.

00:18:52.750 --> 00:18:55.940
I mean, I pretty much never
wake up in the morning and say,

00:18:55.940 --> 00:18:58.959
"I am going to write a thing."

00:18:58.959 --> 00:19:01.500
It's always, you know, what are
the things you have to write?

00:19:04.190 --> 00:19:06.230
I think I read
somewhere that poets

00:19:06.230 --> 00:19:11.290
said that the very
strict poem forms--

00:19:11.290 --> 00:19:13.640
it's the pushing against
the boundaries that

00:19:13.640 --> 00:19:17.060
are what make them interesting,
as opposed to prose

00:19:17.060 --> 00:19:20.050
where you sort of
write whatever.

00:19:20.050 --> 00:19:24.700
But it's more that sometimes the
constraints are kind of funny.

00:19:24.700 --> 00:19:30.130
Like, for the cutscenes
the rule was you did them

00:19:30.130 --> 00:19:32.960
in screenplay format.

00:19:32.960 --> 00:19:37.250
And, you know, it's particular
margins, particular fonts

00:19:37.250 --> 00:19:39.660
and capitalization
and everything.

00:19:39.660 --> 00:19:43.760
And the rule of thumb
was one page per minute,

00:19:43.760 --> 00:19:45.780
or one page per
30 seconds, or-- I

00:19:45.780 --> 00:19:47.840
don't remember what
it was, but it was--

00:19:47.840 --> 00:19:50.860
and so it was, OK, well,
we've got two minutes and 30

00:19:50.860 --> 00:19:52.450
seconds budgeted
for the cutscene

00:19:52.450 --> 00:19:54.810
so it can't be more
than five pages.

00:19:54.810 --> 00:19:58.100
And you can't do the trick
of making the font smaller.

00:19:58.100 --> 00:20:00.980
So there was a lot of
very strange text editing

00:20:00.980 --> 00:20:02.950
where, you know,
someone would say things

00:20:02.950 --> 00:20:07.420
and it was, like, a line plus a
word, and you can't have that.

00:20:07.420 --> 00:20:11.709
That's taking up 10 seconds
or something with the one word

00:20:11.709 --> 00:20:13.250
at the end-- which
it isn't, really--

00:20:13.250 --> 00:20:16.010
but by the measurement,
you know, no.

00:20:16.010 --> 00:20:19.320
It has to be-- so,
you know, I would--

00:20:19.320 --> 00:20:21.910
sometimes you put in a
semicolon instead of a dash

00:20:21.910 --> 00:20:23.090
because it's shorter.

00:20:27.470 --> 00:20:30.022
And then, you
know, you would put

00:20:30.022 --> 00:20:31.980
in the descriptions of
the scenes or the action

00:20:31.980 --> 00:20:36.380
or whatever, which is like,
you know, "view of a study,

00:20:36.380 --> 00:20:39.820
zoom in on the desk which has
an ink well," or whatever.

00:20:39.820 --> 00:20:43.170
And you had to make those also
very short but descriptive

00:20:43.170 --> 00:20:45.180
because you can't just
say, "study" and leave it

00:20:45.180 --> 00:20:48.160
to the artist to
imagine what you mean.

00:20:48.160 --> 00:20:51.440
And the reason that
the rules are like that

00:20:51.440 --> 00:20:53.560
is because the more
description you

00:20:53.560 --> 00:21:00.720
have in the set scene,
in the scene description,

00:21:00.720 --> 00:21:03.290
the more time it's going to
take to show all of the things.

00:21:03.290 --> 00:21:05.240
You know, if you have 15
different things on the desk

00:21:05.240 --> 00:21:06.906
and you want to be
able to see them all,

00:21:06.906 --> 00:21:08.560
you'll want to focus
on it for longer.

00:21:08.560 --> 00:21:12.599
So it's kind of true that the
more lines you have describing

00:21:12.599 --> 00:21:13.890
the scene, the longer it takes.

00:21:13.890 --> 00:21:17.280
But it was a very
strange constraint

00:21:17.280 --> 00:21:19.810
to write to, just because
it seemed so surreal.

00:21:19.810 --> 00:21:22.351
ANDREW GRANT: So you're kind of
gaming-- you had a constraint

00:21:22.351 --> 00:21:25.900
and you're kind of gamed the
constraint to fit on one line.

00:21:25.900 --> 00:21:28.460
And that's actually
not at all surprising.

00:21:28.460 --> 00:21:31.150
I mean, that happens with all
rule sets everywhere, right?

00:21:31.150 --> 00:21:32.140
People game the system.

00:21:32.140 --> 00:21:33.790
LAURA BALDWIN: And I'm sure
screenwriters have to do that,

00:21:33.790 --> 00:21:34.120
too.

00:21:34.120 --> 00:21:35.685
And they're probably--
like, if there

00:21:35.685 --> 00:21:37.768
are screeners out there
they're probably like, oh,

00:21:37.768 --> 00:21:39.092
yeah, use the short words.

00:21:39.092 --> 00:21:40.550
HEATHER ALBANO:
And, interestingly,

00:21:40.550 --> 00:21:43.630
there is an almost identical
constraint in Choice of Games,

00:21:43.630 --> 00:21:46.490
where we only want so many
words on any given screen.

00:21:46.490 --> 00:21:49.310
People are playing these on
a phone a lot of time, right?

00:21:49.310 --> 00:21:52.590
So there's a rule of thumb
that I can no longer remember,

00:21:52.590 --> 00:21:54.860
about how many
words you can have

00:21:54.860 --> 00:22:01.270
before you should have a choice,
and how many words per screen.

00:22:01.270 --> 00:22:03.460
Perhaps you might have two
screens before a choice,

00:22:03.460 --> 00:22:05.293
but probably you shouldn't
do a lot of that.

00:22:05.293 --> 00:22:06.700
You get the idea.

00:22:06.700 --> 00:22:11.660
But so that leads to some
gaming, like with finding

00:22:11.660 --> 00:22:14.220
a shorter word to say
a thing, but it also

00:22:14.220 --> 00:22:16.970
forces you to think
about what you actually

00:22:16.970 --> 00:22:20.730
need to say right now as
opposed to later, or never,

00:22:20.730 --> 00:22:21.345
or, you know.

00:22:21.345 --> 00:22:24.700
And what you said about,
if you need more words

00:22:24.700 --> 00:22:27.090
to paint the scene it's
going to take longer,

00:22:27.090 --> 00:22:29.230
that's definitely true
when it's prose, right?

00:22:29.230 --> 00:22:31.800
If the player needs to know
about-- he's sitting at a desk

00:22:31.800 --> 00:22:36.700
where there's an ink well and a
book of poetry and a something

00:22:36.700 --> 00:22:38.520
else that's going to
be relevant later,

00:22:38.520 --> 00:22:43.660
you have to describe them all
without knocking the player

00:22:43.660 --> 00:22:45.370
over the head, necessarily.

00:22:45.370 --> 00:22:45.630
LAURA BALDWIN: By the
way, there's three things.

00:22:45.630 --> 00:22:46.750
HEATHER ALBANO: By the
way, there's an ink well.

00:22:46.750 --> 00:22:47.360
Yeah.

00:22:47.360 --> 00:22:48.250
Yeah, exactly.

00:22:48.250 --> 00:22:50.040
You just slip it in.

00:22:50.040 --> 00:22:52.540
ANDREW GRANT: So you talk about
these constraints coming in.

00:22:52.540 --> 00:22:54.123
Are these constraints
that were handed

00:22:54.123 --> 00:22:55.440
to you by the rest of team?

00:22:55.440 --> 00:22:58.300
And if so, is
there cases where--

00:22:58.300 --> 00:23:01.030
how much creative controlled do
you have to sort of fight back

00:23:01.030 --> 00:23:02.030
against that sometimes?

00:23:02.030 --> 00:23:04.290
Or is it pretty much
written in stone?

00:23:04.290 --> 00:23:07.169
Or how do you interact
with the team that way?

00:23:07.169 --> 00:23:08.960
HEATHER ALBANO: Well,
when I was at Looking

00:23:08.960 --> 00:23:11.190
Glass I was kind of the
odd jobs person, as I said.

00:23:11.190 --> 00:23:13.950
So I would had really
no creative control,

00:23:13.950 --> 00:23:15.190
but I wasn't looking for it.

00:23:15.190 --> 00:23:19.410
I was happily doing
tasks that I was given.

00:23:19.410 --> 00:23:24.240
Sometimes, I guess, I would
say-- you know, sometimes

00:23:24.240 --> 00:23:26.010
you would get
feedback saying, so

00:23:26.010 --> 00:23:28.310
you need to make these
things more this way,

00:23:28.310 --> 00:23:31.340
and I would be
like, well, it isn't

00:23:31.340 --> 00:23:34.110
possible to make them
more-suspicious-sounding

00:23:34.110 --> 00:23:38.050
and still have them in the
not-suspicious category,

00:23:38.050 --> 00:23:38.789
or, you know.

00:23:38.789 --> 00:23:40.080
But it would be a conversation.

00:23:40.080 --> 00:23:42.410
It was like, OK, the thing
that you're telling me to do

00:23:42.410 --> 00:23:45.110
doesn't make sense, please
clarify, as opposed to,

00:23:45.110 --> 00:23:47.476
I think the thing you're
telling me to do is wrong

00:23:47.476 --> 00:23:48.475
and I want it different.

00:23:51.200 --> 00:23:53.026
And--

00:23:53.026 --> 00:23:54.990
ANDREW GRANT: So there
would be back and forth,

00:23:54.990 --> 00:23:56.667
communication being
the key thing there.

00:23:56.667 --> 00:23:57.500
LAURA BALDWIN: Yeah.

00:23:57.500 --> 00:24:01.380
And, you know, often there
would be a level designer

00:24:01.380 --> 00:24:03.790
who would say things
like, OK, I need

00:24:03.790 --> 00:24:05.870
books for this, this, and this.

00:24:05.870 --> 00:24:12.246
Or can you translate the books
that I've-- I have these pieces

00:24:12.246 --> 00:24:12.870
of information.

00:24:12.870 --> 00:24:14.830
Can you translate them
into Hammerspeak for me?

00:24:14.830 --> 00:24:17.409
And so it was--

00:24:17.409 --> 00:24:18.784
ANDREW GRANT:
What's Hammerspeak?

00:24:18.784 --> 00:24:19.830
LAURA BALDWIN: Ah.

00:24:19.830 --> 00:24:25.460
So the factions in Thief--
there were the Hammerites

00:24:25.460 --> 00:24:30.240
who kind of spoke like
King James bibles,

00:24:30.240 --> 00:24:34.400
and there were the trickster
minions, the Woodsies,

00:24:34.400 --> 00:24:37.478
who spoke weirdly.

00:24:37.478 --> 00:24:42.650
And that's kind of
the-- you know, they-- I

00:24:42.650 --> 00:24:48.460
think Terri Brosius came up
with their dialect originally,

00:24:48.460 --> 00:24:52.960
and it was, you know, "the
Woodsies sing in the treesies."

00:24:52.960 --> 00:24:55.537
And, you know, it was
just a little weird.

00:24:55.537 --> 00:24:57.120
ANDREW GRANT: A
little crazy, kind of.

00:24:57.120 --> 00:24:57.953
LAURA BALDWIN: Yeah.

00:24:57.953 --> 00:25:01.740
And it tended to be
not very grammatical

00:25:01.740 --> 00:25:04.070
and there were a lot
of diminutives on it.

00:25:07.030 --> 00:25:09.660
But it made them
all sound like they

00:25:09.660 --> 00:25:11.930
were from the same
subculture, and I

00:25:11.930 --> 00:25:14.690
think that that was useful.

00:25:14.690 --> 00:25:15.947
Where did I start with this?

00:25:15.947 --> 00:25:17.530
ANDREW GRANT: You
started with working

00:25:17.530 --> 00:25:18.779
with a team, creative control.

00:25:18.779 --> 00:25:21.610
If there's any-- how
do you manage that,

00:25:21.610 --> 00:25:26.470
or was it frustrating
or any of that?

00:25:26.470 --> 00:25:28.550
LAURA BALDWIN: I can't
do artists stuff,

00:25:28.550 --> 00:25:30.950
and I wasn't very good
at the level des--

00:25:30.950 --> 00:25:32.520
So I don't want the
creative control.

00:25:32.520 --> 00:25:35.086
I want to do the
stuff I'm good at

00:25:35.086 --> 00:25:37.710
and let the other people who are
going at stuff do their stuff.

00:25:37.710 --> 00:25:39.434
That's--

00:25:39.434 --> 00:25:41.100
HEATHER ALBANO: I
think that's certainly

00:25:41.100 --> 00:25:42.580
the attitude I
would take if I were

00:25:42.580 --> 00:25:44.710
working on a video game,
which I haven't done yet.

00:25:44.710 --> 00:25:47.300
Maybe someday.

00:25:47.300 --> 00:25:49.500
Because I have great
respect for people

00:25:49.500 --> 00:25:51.560
who can do visual storytelling.

00:25:51.560 --> 00:25:53.270
I have no artistic
ability myself.

00:25:53.270 --> 00:25:57.730
So I would definitely
be pushing that off.

00:25:57.730 --> 00:26:05.507
The Choice of Games-- I'm doing
a solo project the first time,

00:26:05.507 --> 00:26:07.340
galloping towards the
end of a solo project.

00:26:07.340 --> 00:26:10.310
The other ones I have done
have been co-authored,

00:26:10.310 --> 00:26:14.970
and so there was-- the
first one certainly I

00:26:14.970 --> 00:26:17.090
was kind of a junior
partner, learning.

00:26:17.090 --> 00:26:20.470
And so the Choice of Broadsides
was the first game I worked on,

00:26:20.470 --> 00:26:23.180
and when I joined the team
it was all storyboarded.

00:26:23.180 --> 00:26:24.640
And so it was a
matter of, right,

00:26:24.640 --> 00:26:26.306
well, I'm going to
learn how to do this,

00:26:26.306 --> 00:26:31.590
so I'll take that scene
to start with, you know?

00:26:31.590 --> 00:26:35.130
The second game, Choice of
Romance, Adam Strong-Morse

00:26:35.130 --> 00:26:37.890
and I were definitely
colleagues.

00:26:37.890 --> 00:26:41.320
And so there's a give
and take in a-- well,

00:26:41.320 --> 00:26:42.589
any kind of partnership.

00:26:42.589 --> 00:26:44.380
Any kind of creative
partnership, for sure,

00:26:44.380 --> 00:26:46.890
where you have two people
with different opinions

00:26:46.890 --> 00:26:49.220
on how to do x and y and z.

00:26:49.220 --> 00:26:53.960
And, you know, we have a pretty
solid working relationship.

00:26:53.960 --> 00:27:01.090
The one I'm doing solo has been
both freeing and terrifying

00:27:01.090 --> 00:27:05.825
in that I have
creative control-- yay.

00:27:05.825 --> 00:27:06.450
It's wonderful.

00:27:06.450 --> 00:27:10.510
It's totally my story,
and that's phenomenal,

00:27:10.510 --> 00:27:12.350
and it does mean,
however, that when

00:27:12.350 --> 00:27:16.130
I don't know how to do something
there are times when I do kind

00:27:16.130 --> 00:27:17.764
of wish I had a
co-author to say,

00:27:17.764 --> 00:27:19.680
I actually don't have
any good ideas for this.

00:27:19.680 --> 00:27:20.670
Can you--?

00:27:20.670 --> 00:27:22.770
What I do have is a
very, very good editor.

00:27:22.770 --> 00:27:25.950
And so we work in
pretty close partnership

00:27:25.950 --> 00:27:28.530
where I can-- for
instance, last week--

00:27:28.530 --> 00:27:31.560
write her an email after a
playtesting session saying,

00:27:31.560 --> 00:27:34.630
I think we might
have to eliminate

00:27:34.630 --> 00:27:36.170
this section completely.

00:27:36.170 --> 00:27:38.390
If we do it we'll cause
these other problems,

00:27:38.390 --> 00:27:41.430
but if we don't, I don't know
how to solve these problems.

00:27:41.430 --> 00:27:43.770
Which do you think?

00:27:43.770 --> 00:27:45.650
Leading to a two
hour conference call

00:27:45.650 --> 00:27:49.090
where we came up with a third
option, which I would never

00:27:49.090 --> 00:27:50.545
have come up with
by myself, which

00:27:50.545 --> 00:27:52.086
meant we didn't have
to cut the scene

00:27:52.086 --> 00:27:54.180
and we solved the
problems a different way.

00:27:54.180 --> 00:27:55.180
ANDREW GRANT:
That's really cool.

00:27:55.180 --> 00:27:56.090
HEATHER ALBANO: So
hooray for editors.

00:27:56.090 --> 00:27:58.548
ANDREW GRANT: I really like
the fact that you mention that,

00:27:58.548 --> 00:28:00.660
as you're playtesting your
work and it's not done.

00:28:00.660 --> 00:28:04.124
You're playtesting your writing,
which I think is awesome.

00:28:04.124 --> 00:28:06.540
And so that's a great example
of what we're talking about,

00:28:06.540 --> 00:28:08.425
where playtesting
totally just told you

00:28:08.425 --> 00:28:10.120
that something wasn't working.

00:28:10.120 --> 00:28:11.775
Does that happen a lot?

00:28:11.775 --> 00:28:13.025
HEATHER ALBANO: Unfortunately.

00:28:13.025 --> 00:28:14.470
Well, I mean,
fortunately, right?

00:28:14.470 --> 00:28:16.230
Because you'd much
rather have it

00:28:16.230 --> 00:28:18.800
when it's still under
your control than when

00:28:18.800 --> 00:28:20.530
it's out in the wild, right?

00:28:20.530 --> 00:28:30.950
So the Codename Cygnus
thing I was the lead writer,

00:28:30.950 --> 00:28:34.180
so I have a lot of influence,
a lot of control of the script,

00:28:34.180 --> 00:28:34.680
right?

00:28:34.680 --> 00:28:37.810
It was me and the Creative
Director, John Myers,

00:28:37.810 --> 00:28:39.360
working together on it.

00:28:39.360 --> 00:28:42.310
But John was in
charge of production,

00:28:42.310 --> 00:28:45.430
so I actually wasn't involved
in the playtesting for that.

00:28:45.430 --> 00:28:47.700
I would get notes that
were along the lines of,

00:28:47.700 --> 00:28:50.300
this dialogue sequence
is running way long,

00:28:50.300 --> 00:28:51.780
we need to cut it.

00:28:51.780 --> 00:28:53.260
You get the idea.

00:28:53.260 --> 00:28:57.620
The Choice of Game stuff I have
been much more in the trenches,

00:28:57.620 --> 00:29:02.760
like with this game I'm working
on now, my solo project.

00:29:02.760 --> 00:29:06.760
I'm buying dinner for friends
and sitting behind them

00:29:06.760 --> 00:29:09.440
and watching them play it
because it's the only way I

00:29:09.440 --> 00:29:13.217
can tell when they're confused.

00:29:13.217 --> 00:29:14.800
You can ask people
to write you notes,

00:29:14.800 --> 00:29:17.350
and they will, and
they mean well,

00:29:17.350 --> 00:29:18.930
but they never
remember everything.

00:29:18.930 --> 00:29:21.180
And so when you're sitting
there and somebody's taking

00:29:21.180 --> 00:29:24.170
10 minutes to make a
choice you can ask,

00:29:24.170 --> 00:29:26.605
so what are you
thinking right now?

00:29:26.605 --> 00:29:28.230
And you can get an
idea of whether they

00:29:28.230 --> 00:29:32.410
have no idea what's going
on, which was actually

00:29:32.410 --> 00:29:37.136
where the problem in this most
recent-- that the player was

00:29:37.136 --> 00:29:39.260
utterly confused and that
wasn't the first time I'd

00:29:39.260 --> 00:29:40.435
gotten that feedback.

00:29:40.435 --> 00:29:41.810
Although it was
the first time it

00:29:41.810 --> 00:29:45.240
was utter confusion,
rather than mild confusion.

00:29:45.240 --> 00:29:47.351
Or whether the player
is so engrossed

00:29:47.351 --> 00:29:49.850
that they want to make sure
they do exactly the right thing,

00:29:49.850 --> 00:29:51.220
which is a fine response.

00:29:51.220 --> 00:29:55.082
And they can take 10 minutes
if that's what I need to do.

00:29:55.082 --> 00:29:56.730
So yes, I've sort
of wandered away

00:29:56.730 --> 00:29:58.572
from-- what was the
original question?

00:29:58.572 --> 00:29:59.530
ANDREW GRANT: Playtest.

00:29:59.530 --> 00:30:00.080
You found it.

00:30:00.080 --> 00:30:01.010
You do it all the time.

00:30:01.010 --> 00:30:02.551
In fact, you're
going out of your way

00:30:02.551 --> 00:30:07.032
to do it on the solo project
which is mostly writing,

00:30:07.032 --> 00:30:08.740
and you're still
playtesting a lot, which

00:30:08.740 --> 00:30:09.580
I think is really fascinating.

00:30:09.580 --> 00:30:10.516
You mentioned an
editor, you have

00:30:10.516 --> 00:30:12.430
to imagine-- so you've
written books as well.

00:30:12.430 --> 00:30:13.263
HEATHER ALBANO: Yes.

00:30:13.263 --> 00:30:15.759
ANDREW GRANT: Do
you playtest books?

00:30:15.759 --> 00:30:16.800
HEATHER ALBANO: Um, yeah.

00:30:16.800 --> 00:30:17.674
I do, actually.

00:30:17.674 --> 00:30:19.590
You don't call it that
in traditional fiction,

00:30:19.590 --> 00:30:20.220
but absolutely.

00:30:20.220 --> 00:30:22.927
You have drafts, and I belong to
the Cambridge fiction workshop.

00:30:22.927 --> 00:30:24.760
LAURA BALDWIN: My husband
gets really grumpy

00:30:24.760 --> 00:30:27.502
when I call him a
playtester instead of QA.

00:30:27.502 --> 00:30:28.460
ANDREW GRANT: Who this?

00:30:28.460 --> 00:30:29.640
Say that again?

00:30:29.640 --> 00:30:31.990
LAURA BALDWIN: So
Jerry works in QA

00:30:31.990 --> 00:30:34.080
and I often refer to
him as a playtester

00:30:34.080 --> 00:30:36.412
and he's like, it's not
actually playtesting.

00:30:36.412 --> 00:30:38.120
HEATHER ALBANO: Is he
QA-- not for games?

00:30:38.120 --> 00:30:39.060
LAURA BALDWIN: Not
for games, yeah.

00:30:39.060 --> 00:30:39.851
HEATHER ALBANO: OK.

00:30:39.851 --> 00:30:40.500
All right.

00:30:40.500 --> 00:30:41.460
That's hilarious then.

00:30:44.890 --> 00:30:47.670
ANDREW GRANT: So Laura,
have you had experiences

00:30:47.670 --> 00:30:51.090
with playtesting being
essential or showing

00:30:51.090 --> 00:30:52.690
you stuff you didn't expect?

00:30:52.690 --> 00:30:53.900
LAURA BALDWIN: Yeah.

00:30:53.900 --> 00:30:56.600
I mean, in general
for computer games

00:30:56.600 --> 00:30:59.940
you have to have playtesting.

00:30:59.940 --> 00:31:02.800
And I feel like there's actually
a new, modern version where

00:31:02.800 --> 00:31:04.800
you don't playtest and
you ship broken games

00:31:04.800 --> 00:31:08.024
and you just patch as you go,
but I don't approve of that.

00:31:08.024 --> 00:31:09.940
ANDREW GRANT: That is
the new, modern version.

00:31:09.940 --> 00:31:10.660
Yeah.

00:31:10.660 --> 00:31:11.990
LAURA BALDWIN: Looking Glass
had in-house playtesting,

00:31:11.990 --> 00:31:14.690
so you not only had sort
of the naive people saying,

00:31:14.690 --> 00:31:16.960
oh, this is confusing, you
had people who were like,

00:31:16.960 --> 00:31:18.585
OK, I know how is
this, this, and this,

00:31:18.585 --> 00:31:20.880
and they would try to
do all of the things

00:31:20.880 --> 00:31:22.581
and tell you which
ones were broken.

00:31:22.581 --> 00:31:24.580
And that's a little bit
more for the programming

00:31:24.580 --> 00:31:25.880
side and the level design side.

00:31:25.880 --> 00:31:30.320
But I guess there was one thing
that came up pretty early,

00:31:30.320 --> 00:31:33.350
was the head designer thought
that it would be really cool

00:31:33.350 --> 00:31:35.110
if there was sort
of a thieves can't.

00:31:35.110 --> 00:31:42.060
And so all of the internal stuff
that the Garret character would

00:31:42.060 --> 00:31:44.370
be saying to himself-- and
sometimes the guards might

00:31:44.370 --> 00:31:48.370
be saying-- they
would use dialects.

00:31:48.370 --> 00:31:51.540
They would say things like,
"eagled" instead of "saw"

00:31:51.540 --> 00:31:57.980
or-- I forget what we
came up with for "heard."

00:31:57.980 --> 00:32:00.970
And he had this idea of it
being very Clockwork Orange

00:32:00.970 --> 00:32:04.300
where it has its own, you know,
internal language that you

00:32:04.300 --> 00:32:06.710
can mostly figure out if
you're paying attention.

00:32:06.710 --> 00:32:11.945
And so my first set of dialogue
stuff was full of this stuff,

00:32:11.945 --> 00:32:13.320
and the playtesters
were like, we

00:32:13.320 --> 00:32:14.760
have no idea what
they're saying.

00:32:14.760 --> 00:32:15.680
This makes no sense.

00:32:15.680 --> 00:32:19.270
They're saying random words
and it tells us nothing.

00:32:19.270 --> 00:32:21.310
And so that all got cut
out, and pretty much

00:32:21.310 --> 00:32:24.820
the only thing that got kept
was the word "taffer," which was

00:32:24.820 --> 00:32:26.585
sort of the generic swear word.

00:32:26.585 --> 00:32:28.440
You know, you would
say, "you taffer,

00:32:28.440 --> 00:32:30.500
I saw you back there,"
because, you know,

00:32:30.500 --> 00:32:33.080
we were trying for
a no-swearing game.

00:32:33.080 --> 00:32:35.720
But sometimes you want
to have character sounds

00:32:35.720 --> 00:32:40.020
like they're swearing so we
had that word and it stayed.

00:32:40.020 --> 00:32:42.420
HEATHER ALBANO: That's awesome.

00:32:42.420 --> 00:32:46.510
I find there's a difference
between testing and playtesting

00:32:46.510 --> 00:32:47.610
though, too.

00:32:47.610 --> 00:32:49.110
ANDREW GRANT: What's
the difference?

00:32:49.110 --> 00:32:51.540
HEATHER ALBANO: Well,
so one is technical.

00:32:51.540 --> 00:32:52.930
Does the game work?

00:32:52.930 --> 00:32:54.000
Are their crashing bugs?

00:32:54.000 --> 00:33:01.560
And we have certainly at Choice
Of, it's two different things.

00:33:01.560 --> 00:33:04.020
There's the, can you
play to the end of it

00:33:04.020 --> 00:33:06.060
without it crashing on you?

00:33:06.060 --> 00:33:06.825
Good.

00:33:06.825 --> 00:33:07.590
All right.

00:33:07.590 --> 00:33:08.200
First level.

00:33:08.200 --> 00:33:09.130
That's great.

00:33:09.130 --> 00:33:11.780
Can you play through it with
it doing the variable hands off

00:33:11.780 --> 00:33:14.250
between the scenes
correctly, or do you suddenly

00:33:14.250 --> 00:33:17.656
find that you're married to this
person instead of that person?

00:33:17.656 --> 00:33:19.780
I mean, problems like
this happen all the time.

00:33:19.780 --> 00:33:25.420
So although my undergrad
degree is in English,

00:33:25.420 --> 00:33:28.010
I did work in consumer
electronics, such

00:33:28.010 --> 00:33:29.510
that I was working
with programmers.

00:33:29.510 --> 00:33:31.990
I was in QA, in
fact, a long time ago

00:33:31.990 --> 00:33:34.780
before I was in marketing.

00:33:34.780 --> 00:33:38.380
And so thinking about it
in terms of the black box

00:33:38.380 --> 00:33:40.540
testing of, are the
variables being passed,

00:33:40.540 --> 00:33:47.460
are the flags being set,
are the typos in the English

00:33:47.460 --> 00:33:49.940
on the screen,
everything capitalize?

00:33:49.940 --> 00:33:52.116
And then there's the
playtesting which is,

00:33:52.116 --> 00:33:53.490
are you delivering
the experience

00:33:53.490 --> 00:33:54.600
you're trying to deliver?

00:33:54.600 --> 00:33:58.445
Which you can only tell by
watching a human being play it.

00:33:58.445 --> 00:33:59.870
ANDREW GRANT: Got it.

00:33:59.870 --> 00:34:01.487
I like that you
split those two apart

00:34:01.487 --> 00:34:03.070
because when we talk
about it in class

00:34:03.070 --> 00:34:04.200
we often don't make
that distinction,

00:34:04.200 --> 00:34:06.658
but I think it's an important
distinction that there's the,

00:34:06.658 --> 00:34:09.330
does it do what we think
it does technically,

00:34:09.330 --> 00:34:12.880
and does it do what we want it
to do emotionally or enjoyably

00:34:12.880 --> 00:34:13.389
or whatever?

00:34:13.389 --> 00:34:15.090
That's has a good distinction.

00:34:15.090 --> 00:34:16.790
HEATHER ALBANO: In
