00:44:19.550 --> 00:44:22.100
are known, rather than things
you have to impose, right?

00:44:22.100 --> 00:44:23.480
So what you have
to figure out is

00:44:23.480 --> 00:44:25.771
a plot that works with this
world and these characters,

00:44:25.771 --> 00:44:28.940
and I'd say it's just a plot.

00:44:28.940 --> 00:44:30.735
And then once you've
got that down you

00:44:30.735 --> 00:44:33.325
can grow into sort
of the other things.

00:44:33.325 --> 00:44:35.700
ANDREW GRANT: That's a good
little way to do it, I think.

00:44:35.700 --> 00:44:37.830
STUDENT: So, something that
Laura mentioned earlier

00:44:37.830 --> 00:44:40.718
was the whole standing
around and listening to MPCs

00:44:40.718 --> 00:44:42.690
talk for, you know, minutes.

00:44:42.690 --> 00:44:46.480
And it seems to me that in
the Shock Games in particular,

00:44:46.480 --> 00:44:48.495
the answer to that
would be audio logs.

00:44:48.495 --> 00:44:49.740
LAURA BALDWIN: Yes.

00:44:49.740 --> 00:44:52.710
STUDENT: A lot more pervasive
than just a shock series.

00:44:52.710 --> 00:44:56.990
And I'm wondering
has that started

00:44:56.990 --> 00:44:59.550
to become too much of a
crutch to sort of get around

00:44:59.550 --> 00:45:02.480
this whole, we want to
do all this exposition

00:45:02.480 --> 00:45:05.110
but we don't want to tie
people down to a location,

00:45:05.110 --> 00:45:10.995
or do you find that there
is a very specific use

00:45:10.995 --> 00:45:14.320
for that kind of [INAUDIBLE]?

00:45:14.320 --> 00:45:18.570
LAURA BALDWIN: So I think that
Shock, in particular, it's

00:45:18.570 --> 00:45:22.190
trying to be sort of
a role playing game

00:45:22.190 --> 00:45:24.579
which at its hallmark has
dialogue trees and stuff,

00:45:24.579 --> 00:45:25.870
except there's no people there.

00:45:25.870 --> 00:45:28.020
And so it's replacing
dialogue trees

00:45:28.020 --> 00:45:29.650
with little monologue trees.

00:45:32.260 --> 00:45:36.860
And so it's both exposition
and also atmosphere setting.

00:45:36.860 --> 00:45:42.300
So I think that actually-- I
thought that worked very well.

00:45:42.300 --> 00:45:46.740
Shock 2 had a lot of
sort of cutscene--

00:45:46.740 --> 00:45:50.471
in engine cutscenes where you
would be going down a corner

00:45:50.471 --> 00:45:51.970
and there would be
a window and then

00:45:51.970 --> 00:45:52.990
there would be
something that happens

00:45:52.990 --> 00:45:54.323
on the other side of the window.

00:45:54.323 --> 00:45:58.110
And that felt a little bit
more like the Thief listening

00:45:58.110 --> 00:46:00.890
to people talk, because it
would be this scripted thing

00:46:00.890 --> 00:46:04.010
to happen that you would
have to watch, or not watch,

00:46:04.010 --> 00:46:07.590
and it would take
place whether or not

00:46:07.590 --> 00:46:10.320
you were paying attention to it.

00:46:10.320 --> 00:46:13.070
And then it always had to be
built so that you couldn't

00:46:13.070 --> 00:46:15.012
interact with it
because you didn't want

00:46:15.012 --> 00:46:16.970
it to be the case that
you saved the person who

00:46:16.970 --> 00:46:19.360
was being killed, or whatever.

00:46:19.360 --> 00:46:22.220
But yeah, the audio logs
felt like, I thought,

00:46:22.220 --> 00:46:27.320
were a nicely atmospheric
way to do text stumps.

00:46:27.320 --> 00:46:30.570
ANDREW GRANT: Yeah, the question
was, is it overused now?

00:46:30.570 --> 00:46:33.970
And I don't know-- I
imagine, just like any trick

00:46:33.970 --> 00:46:36.300
you use in a game,
if everyone does it,

00:46:36.300 --> 00:46:38.240
yeah, it'll be overused.

00:46:38.240 --> 00:46:41.530
But in some games
it's the right tool.

00:46:41.530 --> 00:46:44.812
In some games it's not.

00:46:44.812 --> 00:46:46.270
STUDENT: Just
following up on that,

00:46:46.270 --> 00:46:51.640
it seems to be a very similar
function to, say, written

00:46:51.640 --> 00:46:55.280
books that you find around in a
game like Skyrim or something.

00:46:55.280 --> 00:46:59.860
It's such a global thing
[INAUDIBLE] building it.

00:46:59.860 --> 00:47:04.050
But because you hear it
as opposed to read it,

00:47:04.050 --> 00:47:07.314
it's something that you can
do while doing other things,

00:47:07.314 --> 00:47:08.736
you know?

00:47:08.736 --> 00:47:12.054
You can go ahead and move
the garbage cans while you're

00:47:12.054 --> 00:47:13.476
receiving all this information.

00:47:13.476 --> 00:47:20.215
And I'm wondering, if
that diminishes its value,

00:47:20.215 --> 00:47:22.640
because you don't really
have to pay attention to it

00:47:22.640 --> 00:47:24.888
and you can just kind
of like be the pack rat

00:47:24.888 --> 00:47:26.762
and collect all the
audio logs without really

00:47:26.762 --> 00:47:27.975
caring about any of that.

00:47:27.975 --> 00:47:32.320
Or is it more prevalent
because there's

00:47:32.320 --> 00:47:33.570
no reason to avoid them?

00:47:33.570 --> 00:47:36.847
It doesn't stop you
from getting around.

00:47:36.847 --> 00:47:37.680
LAURA BALDWIN: Yeah.

00:47:37.680 --> 00:47:42.200
I mean, I think that I would
listen to all the audio logs,

00:47:42.200 --> 00:47:48.360
but-- what is the--
there are some games that

00:47:48.360 --> 00:47:50.240
have had too many books.

00:47:50.240 --> 00:47:54.220
I could not possibly read all
the books, and so I didn't.

00:47:54.220 --> 00:47:56.840
So I think it's
almost more setting

00:47:56.840 --> 00:48:01.820
the right number for any
particular player's enjoyment.

00:48:01.820 --> 00:48:05.610
And I have no idea how to
pick what the right number is.

00:48:05.610 --> 00:48:09.360
I mean, probably somebody read
all the books in Morrowind.

00:48:09.360 --> 00:48:10.010
I did not.

00:48:12.159 --> 00:48:14.200
ANDREW GRANT: It's
player-specifc too, I imagine.

00:48:14.200 --> 00:48:15.180
LAURA BALDWIN: Yeah.

00:48:15.180 --> 00:48:16.294
ANDREW GRANT: Some players
will read none of them,

00:48:16.294 --> 00:48:16.970
some players will
read all of them.

00:48:16.970 --> 00:48:17.803
LAURA BALDWIN: Yeah.

00:48:17.803 --> 00:48:20.590
But the question
of-- I don't know

00:48:20.590 --> 00:48:23.220
if you even need,
want to try to say,

00:48:23.220 --> 00:48:25.030
well, we don't want
to let the player not

00:48:25.030 --> 00:48:26.302
care about the things.

00:48:26.302 --> 00:48:28.010
I mean, if the players
don't want to care

00:48:28.010 --> 00:48:30.700
that's their choice, I guess.

00:48:34.366 --> 00:48:36.490
I mean, that's a totally
different thing, you know?

00:48:36.490 --> 00:48:38.281
What if people are
playing your game wrong?

00:48:41.820 --> 00:48:42.390
You know?

00:48:42.390 --> 00:48:43.912
HEATHER ALBANO: Nothing
you can do about that once

00:48:43.912 --> 00:48:44.430
it's out there, right?

00:48:44.430 --> 00:48:45.070
LAURA BALDWIN: Yeah.

00:48:45.070 --> 00:48:46.611
You know, so there's
the question of,

00:48:46.611 --> 00:48:49.220
should you be able to use
the mods to let you just

00:48:49.220 --> 00:48:50.280
kill anything?

00:48:50.280 --> 00:48:52.640
Is that playing it wrong?

00:48:52.640 --> 00:48:56.220
Or does everyone get to pick
how they want to play it?

00:48:56.220 --> 00:48:59.384
Is using cheat codes evil
or, you know, letting--

00:48:59.384 --> 00:49:01.050
ANDREW GRANT: Helping
you enjoy it more?

00:49:01.050 --> 00:49:03.930
LAURA BALDWIN: Yeah.

00:49:03.930 --> 00:49:06.650
STUDENT: Is there an analog
of concept art in writing?

00:49:06.650 --> 00:49:10.430
Like, for example
you have a paragraph

00:49:10.430 --> 00:49:13.458
that explains what a character
is that's not in the game?

00:49:13.458 --> 00:49:14.291
HEATHER ALBANO: Yes.

00:49:14.291 --> 00:49:15.704
LAURA BALDWIN: Yeah.

00:49:15.704 --> 00:49:19.010
STUDENT: How often are you
responsible for that as well?

00:49:19.010 --> 00:49:21.490
LAURA BALDWIN: So I guess
that's why we design documents.

00:49:21.490 --> 00:49:24.090
And those are traditionally
not as well kept

00:49:24.090 --> 00:49:25.137
up as they should be.

00:49:25.137 --> 00:49:26.970
So they often describe
the state of the game

00:49:26.970 --> 00:49:28.094
as it was three months ago.

00:49:30.947 --> 00:49:32.030
ANDREW GRANT: [INAUDIBLE].

00:49:35.987 --> 00:49:37.820
LAURA BALDWIN: Those
tend to be written more

00:49:37.820 --> 00:49:41.070
by the higher-level
people than I ever was.

00:49:41.070 --> 00:49:43.450
So there would be the
overall design document.

00:49:43.450 --> 00:49:46.450
Here is what we want
the game to be like.

00:49:46.450 --> 00:49:49.840
Here's what we want
this level to be like.

00:49:49.840 --> 00:49:56.220
But that is a good way of
being sort of a tone reference

00:49:56.220 --> 00:49:59.070
or a gameplay-- here are the
things we were aiming for,

00:49:59.070 --> 00:50:01.840
and you can always go
back and look at that.

00:50:01.840 --> 00:50:04.220
HEATHER ALBANO:
Specifically character.

00:50:04.220 --> 00:50:06.912
You said concept art, so
were you thinking characters

00:50:06.912 --> 00:50:08.120
or were you thinking overall?

00:50:08.120 --> 00:50:09.995
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE]
talked about concept art

00:50:09.995 --> 00:50:13.530
being partly to explain to
the artists what they're

00:50:13.530 --> 00:50:15.764
going to do, partly just
to inspire the team,

00:50:15.764 --> 00:50:17.430
which I thought was
an interesting idea.

00:50:17.430 --> 00:50:18.346
HEATHER ALBANO: Right.

00:50:18.346 --> 00:50:19.030
OK.

00:50:19.030 --> 00:50:20.740
I see that.

00:50:20.740 --> 00:50:24.090
So the games I've worked on--
all the games I've worked on

00:50:24.090 --> 00:50:26.140
actually-- except
for the RPG where

00:50:26.140 --> 00:50:28.640
I was in the
world-building part of it--

00:50:28.640 --> 00:50:32.220
have had character bibles
separate from other design

00:50:32.220 --> 00:50:32.740
documents.

00:50:32.740 --> 00:50:36.470
So there's the design documents
that say Choice of Broadsides

00:50:36.470 --> 00:50:39.820
will have 10 vignettes and this
is the one where you capture

00:50:39.820 --> 00:50:42.826
a prize ship, and here
are the five main choices,

00:50:42.826 --> 00:50:44.200
and here's the
one where you have

00:50:44.200 --> 00:50:48.010
the evil lieutenant over you and
here are the five main choices.

00:50:48.010 --> 00:50:52.070
And so there was that, and
those do fall out of date

00:50:52.070 --> 00:50:54.140
very quickly because
once you're in the code,

00:50:54.140 --> 00:50:56.510
you realize you want
to do different things.

00:50:56.510 --> 00:50:59.555
LAURA BALDWIN: And nobody
likes documentation.

00:50:59.555 --> 00:51:00.680
HEATHER ALBANO: Absolutely.

00:51:00.680 --> 00:51:01.300
Absolutely.

00:51:01.300 --> 00:51:02.550
LAURA BALDWIN: I'm in IT now.

00:51:02.550 --> 00:51:05.390
It's still true.

00:51:05.390 --> 00:51:06.890
HEATHER ALBANO: The
character bibles

00:51:06.890 --> 00:51:11.410
though I have found to
be more inspiring, right?

00:51:11.410 --> 00:51:14.640
And so you sit down and you
say that the-- you can do it

00:51:14.640 --> 00:51:15.680
in a few lines, right?

00:51:15.680 --> 00:51:17.640
That the backstory
of this character

00:51:17.640 --> 00:51:19.720
is this and the things
they care about are this.

00:51:19.720 --> 00:51:25.140
And I recently
learned a technique--

00:51:25.140 --> 00:51:30.050
Richard Dansky from UberSoft
is a friend of a friend,

00:51:30.050 --> 00:51:32.820
and boy, is he a very, very,
very skilled game writer.

00:51:32.820 --> 00:51:39.780
And a technique he referred
to was-- oh dear, what was it?

00:51:39.780 --> 00:51:42.390
It was interview
questions, right?

00:51:42.390 --> 00:51:45.740
But the point is,
you answer them

00:51:45.740 --> 00:51:47.470
in the voice of
the character, not

00:51:47.470 --> 00:51:50.415
just what the character would
answer-- their favorite--

00:51:50.415 --> 00:51:53.220
their best friend is Susan.

00:51:53.220 --> 00:51:59.468
But there's a difference between
a character who says, "oh, you

00:51:59.468 --> 00:52:02.140
know, Bob, he's
always got my back,"

00:52:02.140 --> 00:52:05.510
and, "I first met Susan
when we were in kindergarten

00:52:05.510 --> 00:52:07.990
and we were friends all
through elementary school,

00:52:07.990 --> 00:52:10.450
except for that time when we
had a fight in sixth grade

00:52:10.450 --> 00:52:12.360
over the"-- and, like,
you know something

00:52:12.360 --> 00:52:17.240
about both of the speakers
just from the way they answer.

00:52:17.240 --> 00:52:19.371
LAURA BALDWIN: Most
design documents

00:52:19.371 --> 00:52:20.620
are not necessarily inspiring.

00:52:20.620 --> 00:52:23.950
But something that
is possibly more so

00:52:23.950 --> 00:52:25.840
is the One Minute of Gameplay.

00:52:25.840 --> 00:52:27.610
And it's sort of like
the little narration

00:52:27.610 --> 00:52:30.660
of what you're doing as some
random moment in the game,

00:52:30.660 --> 00:52:32.660
and why is it fun?

00:52:32.660 --> 00:52:34.910
Because why is it fun
is kind of the thing

00:52:34.910 --> 00:52:36.820
that you need to keep
focusing everyone on.

00:52:36.820 --> 00:52:38.890
You know, the point
of the game is not

00:52:38.890 --> 00:52:42.180
to show you the cool art,
or to make you listen

00:52:42.180 --> 00:52:44.550
to my really cool dialogue.

00:52:44.550 --> 00:52:46.090
It's to be fun.

00:52:46.090 --> 00:52:50.390
And I think that if you can
write a One Minute of Gameplay

00:52:50.390 --> 00:52:53.950
which is somewhat inspiring for
your designers and programmers,

00:52:53.950 --> 00:52:55.720
then that's really good.

00:52:58.059 --> 00:52:59.059
ANDREW GRANT: Questions?

00:53:01.921 --> 00:53:04.320
Then I think I will follow
up with one last thing

00:53:04.320 --> 00:53:07.220
and we may have already
used up an answer here,

00:53:07.220 --> 00:53:09.760
but we'll all try it.

00:53:09.760 --> 00:53:11.760
What can you think
of that you didn't

00:53:11.760 --> 00:53:14.740
know when you started
trying to write for games

00:53:14.740 --> 00:53:17.510
that kind of surprised you,
and now you would think

00:53:17.510 --> 00:53:19.510
to yourself, yeah, I
didn't know that, I did not

00:53:19.510 --> 00:53:20.841
expect that to be that way?

00:53:24.849 --> 00:53:26.390
LAURA BALDWIN: I
think the screenplay

00:53:26.390 --> 00:53:27.990
thing was the weirdest.

00:53:27.990 --> 00:53:34.090
Just-- a screenplay has these
fonts and these margins and you

00:53:34.090 --> 00:53:34.927
can't go over the--

00:53:34.927 --> 00:53:36.010
ANDREW GRANT: [INAUDIBLE].

00:53:36.010 --> 00:53:37.240
LAURA BALDWIN: Yeah.

00:53:37.240 --> 00:53:41.117
I gather that you can
submit academic abstracts

00:53:41.117 --> 00:53:42.950
and it has the same
sort of thing, you know,

00:53:42.950 --> 00:53:45.240
no more than 800
characters or whatever.

00:53:45.240 --> 00:53:47.380
But I think that
was the strangest.

00:53:47.380 --> 00:53:51.220
Like, I just had-- that
was a very big surprise.

00:53:51.220 --> 00:53:54.429
Most writing, I think,
feels more natural.

00:53:54.429 --> 00:53:55.220
ANDREW GRANT: Sure.

00:53:55.220 --> 00:53:57.570
HEATHER ALBANO: Screenplays
are pretty specific, yeah.

00:54:03.240 --> 00:54:05.010
Personally speaking,
my biggest surprises

00:54:05.010 --> 00:54:07.680
have all been the positive ones.

00:54:07.680 --> 00:54:08.930
ANDREW GRANT: All right.

00:54:08.930 --> 00:54:10.380
HEATHER ALBANO: I thought
I wanted to write novels--

00:54:10.380 --> 00:54:12.550
and I still think I probably
want to write novels--

00:54:12.550 --> 00:54:17.590
but I didn't expect this to
be as artistically satisfying

00:54:17.590 --> 00:54:19.360
as it has turned out to be.

00:54:19.360 --> 00:54:22.620
Now, granted, I'm in a
pretty narrow writing field.

00:54:22.620 --> 00:54:24.430
What I do is not typical.

00:54:24.430 --> 00:54:26.930
What Laura's done is
more typical of writing

00:54:26.930 --> 00:54:30.110
for the games industry.

00:54:30.110 --> 00:54:33.320
Something that I
think surprises a lot

00:54:33.320 --> 00:54:37.160
of people who have a background
in traditional fiction and then

00:54:37.160 --> 00:54:43.050
transition into writing games--
because I've seen this a lot--

00:54:43.050 --> 00:54:45.176
back in the LARP days we
used to call it the oops

00:54:45.176 --> 00:54:49.050
I forgot to add the interactive
part where you have people

00:54:49.050 --> 00:54:53.680
who are very, very, very skilled
at plots and at character arcs

00:54:53.680 --> 00:54:58.950
and at story arcs and are
not accustomed to having

00:54:58.950 --> 00:55:02.620
to leave room for the player
to interact with the world.

00:55:02.620 --> 00:55:05.070
And this is, I think, a
problem you get specifically

00:55:05.070 --> 00:55:06.780
when you have
somebody transitioning

00:55:06.780 --> 00:55:10.070
from non-interactive fiction
to interactive fiction.

00:55:10.070 --> 00:55:14.490
I think I was fortunate that
I made those mistakes very

00:55:14.490 --> 00:55:18.660
early, when I was running
LARPs when I was in college,

00:55:18.660 --> 00:55:21.930
and learned those lessons fast.

00:55:21.930 --> 00:55:23.510
ANDREW GRANT: Right.

00:55:23.510 --> 00:55:27.280
HEATHER ALBANO: It's sort
of-- at least at that time

00:55:27.280 --> 00:55:30.840
doing Quest at
Wesleyan and it was

00:55:30.840 --> 00:55:33.700
one of the typical
first-time Jam mistakes,

00:55:33.700 --> 00:55:36.860
was putting too much
on their staff members,

00:55:36.860 --> 00:55:38.390
their non-player
characters and not

00:55:38.390 --> 00:55:40.510
giving enough room for
the players to, you know,

00:55:40.510 --> 00:55:45.224
play the game and affect the
world and impact what happens.

00:55:45.224 --> 00:55:46.890
You can't impact what
happens because we

00:55:46.890 --> 00:55:48.140
have this scene for the end.

00:55:48.140 --> 00:55:49.570
No.

00:55:49.570 --> 00:55:51.556
It's not a play.

00:55:51.556 --> 00:55:52.680
ANDREW GRANT: Right, right.

00:55:52.680 --> 00:55:53.760
LAURA BALDWIN: I
have another answer.

00:55:53.760 --> 00:55:54.926
ANDREW GRANT: OK, excellent.

00:55:54.926 --> 00:55:57.430
It is awesome how cool
your writing sounds

00:55:57.430 --> 00:56:00.930
when it is spoken by an actual
professional voice actor,

00:56:00.930 --> 00:56:02.934
and I did not expect that.

00:56:02.934 --> 00:56:04.970
ANDREW GRANT: As
opposed to programmers?

00:56:04.970 --> 00:56:08.530
LAURA BALDWIN: Or by me, like
when I say it in my head.

00:56:08.530 --> 00:56:11.030
And then, you know,
there was a little ritual

00:56:11.030 --> 00:56:14.720
at the end of Thief where the
Dark God is doing this ritual

00:56:14.720 --> 00:56:16.660
and I was like, well,
he's doing this thing,

00:56:16.660 --> 00:56:17.860
he has to say something.

00:56:17.860 --> 00:56:20.010
You always have to have
a poem for rituals.

00:56:20.010 --> 00:56:21.820
So I wrote him a
poem to be saying.

00:56:21.820 --> 00:56:23.800
And then the actor
for Constantine

00:56:23.800 --> 00:56:31.050
came in and spoke it in his Dark
God voice, and it was awesome.

00:56:31.050 --> 00:56:35.300
And then even better was when
it was translated into French

00:56:35.300 --> 00:56:39.030
